  <section class="essay-opener" id="opener">
    <p>&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t miss the forest for the trees&rdquo; is good advice until it isn&rsquo;t. The idiom fits when one is tangled in particulars, unable to see the system at work, and losing sight of the point<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">AKA being stuck in an A-hole.</span></span>. But abstraction has its own failure mode: the forest fills the view, and the tree drops out. One is captive to the model, serving the model, not the thing.</p>

    <p>From time to time, you have to put your hands back on the wood.</p>

    <p>Anyone who has worked seriously with hard material &ndash; wood, stone, metal, code &ndash; knows the moment when the system-level view stops helping and you have to get back down to the thing itself&hellip;</p>

  </section>

  <section class="essay-section essay-section-consider" id="consider">
    <h2>Consider the tree</h2>

    <p>A tree is a very slow civilization of fibers and fluids.</p>

    <p>Trees have been &ldquo;solving&rdquo; design and engineering problems a lot longer than us. Several hundred million years, conservatively.</p>

    <p>But before there were trees, something else tried to be tall.</p>

  </section>

  <section class="essay-section essay-section-protobella" id="protobella">
    <h2>A fungus called Protobella</h2>

    <figure class="essay-figure essay-figure-inbody">
      <img src="/img/essay/consider-the-tree/prototaxites-dawson-1888.webp" alt="Dawson's 1888 reconstruction of Prototaxites" />
      <figcaption>Dawson&rsquo;s 1888 reconstruction. He was wrong.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>Eight-meter trunks rose out of a treeless landscape four hundred million years ago, when nothing on land was bigger than your left thumb. <em><a href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/mystery-prototaxites-tower-fossils-may-represent-a-newly-discovered-kind-of/">Prototaxites</a></em> &ndash; Protobella, in the privacy of my own head &ndash; confused every paleontologist who tried to sort it. A primitive conifer. An algae. A liverwort. Every fungal phylum on offer. Each category almost worked.</p>

    <p>A Smithsonian botanist named Francis Hueber cut thin sections of those specimens under a microscope for forty years and died in 2019 sure it was a fungus. In <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.aec6277" target="_blank" rel="noopener">2026</a>, new tests on the cell walls turned up lignin-like chemistry and no fungal biomarkers at all.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Chitin is the structural molecule common to all fungi &ndash; insect exoskeletons too.</span></span> The tests placed it outside any living lineage. A branch of eukaryotic life that left no descendants.</p>

    <p>A parallel attempt at the tree-form, by a lineage that didn&rsquo;t reach the present. By the end of the Devonian, the columns disappeared. We still don&rsquo;t know why.</p>

    <p>Branching solved it. The design kept evolving for hundreds of millions of years. Branches, leaves, shade &ndash; and by then, animals around to use them. Branching was the solution to being tall and photosynthesizing. The cost was knots. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lindy_effect" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lindy</a> here refers to the strategies and tactics evolved over trial and error, not the individual tree<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">A reader trained on Deleuze and Guattari may notice that the &ldquo;tree&rdquo; here is doing the opposite of <em>their</em> tree &mdash; the arborescent figure of hierarchy they set the rhizome against. The literal-biological tree never matched the strawman: crown grown lopsided for light, roots tangled with the next tree&rsquo;s, mycorrhizal threads ferrying sugar and signal across species lines underground, sap moving in whichever direction the year demands. What I&rsquo;m describing is closer to what they&rsquo;d call rhizomatic.</span></span>. The branching solution is older than dinosaurs. <a href="/shelf/#design" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Design thinking</a> is sixty-some years on this planet.</p>

  </section>

  <section class="essay-section essay-section-alba" id="alba">
    <h2>A tree called Alba</h2>

    <p>Consider the tree.</p>

    <figure class="essay-figure essay-figure-inbody">
      <img
        src="/img/essay/consider-the-tree/alba-800w.webp"
        srcset="/img/essay/consider-the-tree/alba-800w.webp 1x, /img/essay/consider-the-tree/alba.webp 2x"
        alt="Alba, a large white oak on a slope above Sugar Creek in Edgewood, Atlanta, receiving a clean bill of health from an arborist."
      />
      <figcaption>Alba receiving a recent clean bill of health from arborist Peter Jenkins. Photo: <a href="https://meetalba.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Meet Alba</a>.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>One in particular. Ten minutes from my desk, on a slope above Sugar Creek, four white oaks have been standing since before the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Atlanta" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Battle of Atlanta</a>. I walk the dog there. The largest &ndash; <a href="https://meetalba.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Alba, the neighborhood calls her</a><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Largest white oak (<em>Quercus alba</em> &ndash; hence the name) inside Atlanta city limits. 69-inch DBH; estimated 200&ndash;250 years old; recently certified healthy by Peter Jenkins of <a href="https://treeinspection.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TreeInspection.com</a>. If preserved, could live another five hundred years. The four oaks sit on a 6-acre parcel off Vaughn Street in Edgewood, rezoned for Planned Development &ndash; Housing in 2007. Source: <a href="https://meetalba.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Meet Alba</a>.</span></span> &ndash; is around two hundred and fifty years old. Atlanta is one hundred and seventy.</p>

    <p>Whatever value Alba has now lives in the handful of neighbors who learned her name.</p>
  </section>

