  <section class="essay-section essay-definitions-section" id="vocabulary">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">Vocabulary</div></div>
    <p>Before moving on, a few handy woodworking terms&hellip;</p>

    <dl class="essay-definitions">
      <dt><strong>rive</strong> <span class="essay-definitions-meta">/raɪv/ &middot; verb.</span></dt>
      <dd>To split wood along the grain with a froe and a mallet. Old Norse <em>rífa,</em> &ldquo;to tear, scratch&rdquo; &ndash; same root as <em>rift, riven, reef.</em> You aren&rsquo;t cutting the wood. You&rsquo;re persuading it to come apart along a line it was already going to take if you waited long enough. Stronger than a sawn board, because the fibers stay continuous. The downside is you can&rsquo;t rive anything that didn&rsquo;t intend to split. When people say they&rsquo;re &ldquo;working with the grain,&rdquo; they usually mean cutting along the direction of the fibers, not against them. Riving is the only technique that does what the phrase actually says: you don&rsquo;t cut along the grain, you let the grain choose where the cut goes. Modern English carries this forward in another direction: a <em>riven</em> family, a <em>riven</em> country. The word didn&rsquo;t move; we just stopped noticing where it came from.</dd>

      <dt><strong>green wood</strong></dt>
      <dd>Wood still alive, or recently so. Moisture content high enough that the cells haven&rsquo;t shrunk back. Moves while you work it. Keeps moving for months after you&rsquo;re done. Carpenters who only know kiln-dried boards treat green wood like a problem; anyone who works it learns the movement is information.</dd>

      <dt><strong>plane</strong> <span class="essay-definitions-meta">/pleɪn/ &middot; noun, verb.</span></dt>
      <dd>A hand tool: a sharpened blade set in a body of wood or iron, tuned to shave a thin curl off a board. Also what you do with it. Not the geometry kind, not the airplane kind. The thing on a workbench. In the right hands, it leaves a surface smoother than sandpaper ever will. In the wrong hands, it digs a hole.</dd>

      <dt><strong>grain</strong></dt>
      <dd>The direction the wood fibers go. Sometimes obvious, sometimes not. Reading the grain is the difference between a clean cut and a torn-up surface; it&rsquo;s also the difference between a workpiece that holds and a workpiece that splits.</dd>

      <dt><strong>heartwood</strong></dt>
      <dd>The dense inner core of a mature tree, darker than the wood around it. Dead, but load-bearing: it has stopped growing, stopped moving water, and become the part that holds the rest of the tree up. The living wood is the thin layer at the edge.</dd>

      <dt><strong>knot</strong></dt>
      <dd>Where a branch grew out of the trunk, and the tree buried it under ring after ring of new wood, the way an oyster embalms a speck of grit in layers of pearl. Cut a knot the wrong way and your plane skips. The defect is the tree&rsquo;s memory.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Rope-knots are tied; wood-knots formed. Tied knots come from intention. Formed knots come from biography. Same word, different reading.</span></span></dd>

      <dt><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reaction_wood" target="_blank" rel="noopener">reaction wood</a></strong></dt>
      <dd>Wood the tree produced under load: a trunk leaning into a slope, a sapling pushed by its neighbor. The loaded side lays down different fibers. The board looks normal. It behaves badly. You can&rsquo;t see reaction wood until you cut it, and sometimes not until it warps in your shop a month later.</dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section class="essay-section" id="record">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">Record</div></div>
    <h2>Record</h2>

    <p>Wood records. Each ring dates a year of growth. Each knot dates a branching event. Each scar dates an injury and the response to it. Trees keep no spreadsheets. They write in grain, ring, knot, and scar. Reading a board is reading a biography.</p>

    {# [REDLINE — sentence after "planes the sapwood" needs Lee's hand.
       Current "It skates uselessly across the knot" is conceptually wrong:
       knots don't get skated across, that's clear sapwood. At a knot the
       motion is encounter — less often skates, more often catches/crashes;
       can take the wind out of you when in flow. Claude drafts kept stacking
       carpentry verbs onto an institutional sentence and producing slop.
       Lee writes the replacement. Lines after stay as-is. #}
    <p>Communities are not inert inputs. Institutions are not dimensionally stable. Incentives swell and shrink seasonally. Political moisture content changes. Programs move after installation.</p>

    <p>Institutions carry the same kind of record, and most of it slips past the tools they prefer. What gets filed planes the sapwood. It catches at the knot and reads nothing. A dated knot &ndash; a near-bankruptcy in 2002, an executive transition that swapped the nameplate not the decisions, an impact figure recycled since 2010, an annual report written for what the funder expected to be true &ndash; bears load the way heartwood does.</p>

    <p>Institutionalized procedures, obsolete-seeming roles, accumulated tacit norms &mdash; these are the heartwood. Organizations that try to stay metabolically active all the way through their structure &ndash; all sapwood, no heartwood &ndash; are trading structural integrity for short-term nutrient throughput. They&rsquo;ll grow fast and blow over.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">The tree doesn&rsquo;t know it&rsquo;s doing this. Abscission isn&rsquo;t a decision; phloem doesn&rsquo;t allocate. The mechanism runs below the level of agency. Reading the diagnosis doesn&rsquo;t change the mechanism &ndash; only how an organization responds to it. The frame names what&rsquo;s happening. It doesn&rsquo;t tell you what to cut.</span></span></p>

    <p>Most of Alba is dead.</p>

    <p>Most of the air came from things buried before they could decay.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Respiration and decay consume roughly 99% of the oxygen photosynthesis produces. Atmospheric O&#8322; accumulated, over billions of years, only because a small fraction of organic carbon got buried in sediments before it could be respired back to CO&#8322;. Catling &amp; Claire (2005), <em>How Earth&rsquo;s atmosphere evolved to an oxic state.</em></span></span></p>

    <p>You hear the knot in stories. You usually learn what you really need to know at the bar, after the conference. Or in DMs. Or when the recording stops. Not in meetings.</p>

    <p>Operators know. The operating narrative is everything &ndash; the story that connects operations to effectiveness, whatever the values and mission statement say. As Monika Krause argues in <em><a href="https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/G/bo17888868.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Good Project</a></em>, most NGOs have their narrative wrong. When the narrative is wrong, mission and operations decouple<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Meyer &amp; Rowan, &ldquo;<a href="https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/10.1086/226550" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Institutionalized Organizations: Formal Structure as Myth and Ceremony</a>,&rdquo; <em>American Journal of Sociology</em> 83.2 (1977): 340&ndash;363. Formal structures get adopted to confer legitimacy, then decoupled from actual operating practice. The formal record and the operating record stop tracking each other.</span></span>. The tacit knowledge that actually runs the place lives scattered in heads.</p>

    <p>An organization that cannot read its own record cannot locate its own knots. Non-profits and for-profits alike. No one sees the whole story from within &ndash; an <a href="https://anxiaomina.substack.com/p/elephant-problems-the-limitations" target="_blank" rel="noopener">elephant problem</a>.</p>

    <p>Atlanta started branding itself &ldquo;<a href="https://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/why-atlanta-known-city-forest/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City in a Forest</a>&rdquo; mid-twentieth century. American Forests put the metro region at 48% tree canopy in 1974; Georgia Tech put the city limits at 46.5% in 2018.<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Georgia Tech Center for Spatial Planning Analytics and Visualization, <em>2018 City of Atlanta Urban Tree Canopy Assessment</em>; American Forests, <em>Regional Ecosystem Analysis: Atlanta Metropolitan Area</em> (2001). 1974 figure is metro region, 2018 figure is city limits &ndash; not a clean trend line.</span></span> The decade ending 2018 shed roughly 150 acres a year, mostly to private redevelopment. The cluster of global-health institutions whose campuses sit a few miles apart here &ndash; I was at <a href="https://www.sph.emory.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Rollins</a> for grad school, in the middle of it &ndash; runs the same dynamic at organizational scale.</p>

