  <section class="essay-section" id="knots-self">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">I work with knots</div></div>
    <h2>I work with knots</h2>

    <p>I've gathered a set of useful tools along the way, and made a few of my own. Most of my consulting tools are for handling <em>knots</em>: places where the grain runs in several directions at once, and the next cut is not obvious.</p>

    <p>The cut depends on the knot. Reading one starts mechanically &ndash; how it formed, how the grain runs through it, where it fails.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="essay-section" id="how-knots">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">How I think about knots</div></div>
    <h2>How I think about knots</h2>

    <p>A knot begins as a branch &ndash; and the branch began as a reach for light.</p>

    <p>Each year, with the turn of the seasons, the tree lays down another ring of wood around its core, just beneath the bark. Slowly the trunk thickens around the living branch, engulfing it ring by ring. Year after year, ring on ring, knot on knot.</p>

    <p>Sped up, the tree would look animate. Bark faintly crackling along the trunk&rsquo;s slow swell, microfissures opening into warm, gnarled retreats for insects. Pale new wood lapping over the last with each rainy season. Meanwhile the buried branch, still carrying water up through the trunk to leaves beyond the bark, keeps drinking.</p>

    <p>A knot is engulfed tissue, still drinking.</p>

    <p>A sawyer reads for them. Bark bumps, branch scars, the way the tree leaned. The log gets oriented on the carriage accordingly.</p>

    <hr class="essay-divider" />

    <p>The tree keeps growing toward the sun, laying down new road each spring on its journey toward the sky (while the weather's good for construction). Inside and out, the tree works the season for what it can get. Moisture, warmth, and light.</p>

    <p>At a knot, the grain takes the long way around.</p>

    <p>Around the knot, the fibers crowd together, cross paths, switch direction without warning. Sometimes the wood hardens around the knot, glassy and resinous, and your chisel chatters across it. Sometimes the fibers tear loose all at once and leave a divot where a smooth cut was supposed to be. Wood that read clear a few inches ago judders under the plane<span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Earlier draft similes for these same mechanisms, dropped from the prose because the verbs (chatters, judders) carry it: the grain bending the way spacetime bends around a black hole; the chisel chattering like a skipped record; the plane juddering like a shopping cart with one bad wheel; worst case, the plane meeting a knot the way a car meets a telephone pole.</span></span>.</p>

    <p>This is usually where people begin blaming their tools.</p>

    <p>The knot holds harder than the wood around it under certain loads, and fails first across the grain.</p>

    <p>You learn to read ahead a little. The habit carries.</p>

    <hr class="essay-divider" />

    <p>Living systems make knots. No knots, no branches. No branches, no peaches, nesting places, or afternoon shade. No shade, no tree to fall asleep against.</p>

    <p>You don&rsquo;t fix a gnarled oak. You learn to read what the tree has written, reckon with how the grain bends around the knot, and follow the cut the grain itself wants.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="essay-section" id="common-knots">
    <div class="essay-image-slot" aria-hidden="true"><div class="essay-image-placeholder">Common knots and useful tools</div></div>
    <h2>Common knots and useful tools</h2>

    <p>To know which tool to reach for, we have to examine the knot.</p>

    <p>A knot is a recurring configuration of legitimate pressures that can&rsquo;t all be satisfied at once. Read the shape early.</p>

    <h3>The problem with wicked problems</h3>

    <figure class="essay-figure-inbody">
      <img
        src="/img/essay/consider-the-tree/concepts-become-things.webp"
        alt="A photograph of geometric solids - spheres, cones, cylinders, cubes, prisms - arranged in a desert landscape, overlaid with the meme caption 'Everybody gangsta until concepts become things.'"
      />
      <figcaption>Found meme. Original artwork: <em>Metamorphosis</em>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbert_Bayer" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Herbert Bayer</a> (1936).</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>&ldquo;Wicked problems&rdquo; is a frame for hard problems. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/14494035.2019.1617971">It&rsquo;s been used too many ways to mean much.</a> Once I've called something wicked, I know it's hard. I don't know what kind of hard, or what to do next.</p>

    <p>A better diagnostic names the knot, and the cut that fits it. A few I work with often:</p>

    <p><strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart%27s_law" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Goodhart&rsquo;s Law</a>.</strong> <em>(<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campbell%27s_law" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Campbell&rsquo;s Law</a> &middot; Tyranny of Metrics)</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Charles Goodhart&rsquo;s original 1975 formulation: <em>&ldquo;Any observed statistical regularity will tend to collapse once pressure is placed upon it for control purposes.&rdquo;</em> The Strathern compression is the line that travels: <em>&ldquo;When a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure.&rdquo;</em></span></span> An indicator starts as protection against drift, then becomes the thing the system optimizes. Staff know which number matters; they learn to game it whether or not the work moves with it. The number is sapwood. The actual grain runs somewhere underneath. Rotate the measures. Triangulate with what the indicator can&rsquo;t see. Leave the number under-optimized.</p>

    <p><strong>Capability Trap.</strong> <em>(Andrews, Pritchett &amp; Woolcock)</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Matt Andrews, Lant Pritchett &amp; Michael Woolcock, <em><a href="https://library.oapen.org/handle/20.500.12657/31857" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Building State Capability: Evidence, Analysis, Action</a></em> (Oxford, 2017). Pairs with <em>premature load bearing</em> &ndash; the related failure mode where a new mechanism is asked to carry weight before the underlying capacity exists.</span></span> Organizations learn to look functional before they learn to function. Plans, dashboards, organograms, all visible; the ordinary work still depends on improvisation. This is reaction wood. The boards lay down straight, and warp a month after delivery. Fewer formal commitments. Permission for the competence to form underneath before the polish is asked of it.</p>

    <p><strong>Isomorphic Mimicry.</strong> <em>(DiMaggio &amp; Powell &middot; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seeing_Like_a_State" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Seeing Like a State</a>)</em><span class="sn-marker" tabindex="0"><span class="sidenote-tooltip">Paul DiMaggio &amp; Walter Powell, &ldquo;The Iron Cage Revisited: Institutional Isomorphism and Collective Rationality in Organizational Fields,&rdquo; <em>American Sociological Review</em> 48 (1983): 147&ndash;160. Three mechanisms: coercive (regulation, funder demands), mimetic (copying perceived legitimate forms under uncertainty), normative (professional training and credentialing). The development-policy variant &ndash; <em>isomorphic mimicry</em> &ndash; comes out of the Building State Capability work and emphasizes mimetic adoption of form without the underlying capacity.</span></span> Institutions import the form of legitimacy from somewhere else because that&rsquo;s what funders and peers recognize. Inside, the real decisions still travel through an older informal architecture. The surface grain was planed to match the room. What&rsquo;s load-bearing was grown in a different forest. Keep the imported form. Let the actual load shape what&rsquo;s underneath.</p>

    <p><strong>Trust on Demand.</strong> <em>(Trapped Priors)</em> A split that opened in a different cut, years ago, and never closed. Institutions ask for trust where prior experience has trained people to withhold it. Officials hear distrust as misinformation; communities hear urgency as another request to carry risk for someone else&rsquo;s plan. Repair before persuasion: name prior harms, narrow promises, permit refusal.</p>

    <p><strong>Evaluation Theatre.</strong> <em>(Innovation Theater &middot; <a href="/shelf/#bullshit" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Cargo Cult Science</a>)</em> The grain direction was declared in the terms of reference. Nobody read the actual wood. Terms of reference get drafted toward a known landing; inception meetings narrow the questions; everyone in the room already knows which answers are safe. Findings get praised; nothing consequential changes. Precommit to decisions the findings can change. Fund the negative result.</p>

    <p>Most real work has several of these going at once. My job is to work where the story and the material have come apart, and find the next cut.</p>
  </section>

